<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cercocarpus ledifolius </i>is a long-lived, tall shrub to small tree that is characteristic of nutrient and water deficient environments. Plants mainly reproduce by seed and the wind-dispersed seeds germinate best on well-lighted mineral soil. Seedling survivorship increases under the protection of older plants (Marshall 1995a), while browsing contributes to high seedling mortality.<br/>
<br/>
Taxonomic consensus has not been reached on the number of varieties of this taxon. The Jepson Manual recognizes three varieties: var. <i>intermontanus</i>, var. <i>intricatus</i>, and var. <i>ledifolius</i> (Jepson Flora Project 2019). Under this taxonomy, varieties <i>intermontanus</i> and <i>ledifolius</i> are included in this alliance, with var. <i>ledifolius</i> being relatively uncommon compared to var. <i>intermontanus</i>. The USDA PLANTS database recognizes only the two varieties included in this alliance: var. <i>intercedens</i> (a synonym of var. <i>intermontanus</i>) and var. <i>ledifolius</i>. As such, var. <i>intricatus</i> is recognized at the species level as <i>C. intricatus</i> (USDA PLANTS 2001). <i>C. intricatus</i> is included in the <i>Amelanchier utahensis - Cercocarpus montanus - Cercocarpus intricatus</i> alliance (VegCAMP 2020). <br/>
<br/>
The alliance occurs in semi-arid, mountainous habitats of the interior western United States, ranging through the high deserts and mountains of California. Species composition and associated alliances vary regionally. Stands are typically small and patchy and occur on sites with immature, coarse soils such as dry ridges, rocky outcrops, and steep slopes. These sites are often unsuitable for the adjacent coniferous woodlands or forests (NatureServe 2019). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
