<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">The role of fire on <i>Cercocarpus ledifolius </i>stand establishment and maintenance is unclear in California. Arno and Wilson (1986) reported a 13- to 22-year mean fire return interval for stands of <i>Cercocarpus ledifolius </i>in Idaho. While Schultz et al. (1990) reported all age distributions in a study of <i>C. ledifolius</i> stands in Nevada, which is characteristic of tree-by-tree replacement rather than stand replacing fire. Fire easily kills <i>Cercocarpus ledifolius </i>plants, after which most stand replacement occurs from seed.  Fire suppression has increased fuel loading in east-side stands (Johnson and Smathers 1974). However, increased fuel loading and post-fire stand replacement is ostensibly variable, probably depending on favorable weather for seedling germination and growth. Marshall (1995a) reported both multi-aged and even-aged stands, indicative of variable post-fire response of <i>C. ledifoius </i>. When <i>Cercocarpus ledifolius </i>occurs in other alliances, it usually plays a seral role.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
