    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ac, Ae, Ag, Ai-j, Al, At). Stands are local at montane and subalpine elevations in the central and eastern subsections, including Sugar Creek and Crater Creek cRNAs (Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-d, Gf-p). Stands are widespread in the Warner Mountains, on escarpments and outcrops throughout Devils Garden, and at Raider Basin cRNA (Jensen and Schierenbeck 1990, see Cheng 2004), and are described generally in the section (Young et al. 1977, 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Da-e, Dh, Dj-l). This alliance is widespread in the rocky highlands of the section. Stands are common on the eastern escarpment of the Sierra Nevada associated with <i>Juniperus grandis</i> and pine alliances (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b). Stands in the Lee Vining Canyon area that burned in the past decade show moderate seedling establishment.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). Stands occupy localized ultramafic substrates, exposed ridges at montane elevations in the section, and on greywacke sandstones in the Yolla Bolly Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Keeler-Wolf 1976).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Bb, Bd). Stands are scattered at higher-elevation ranges as isolated patches among <i>Artemisia</i> steppe types (Young et al. 1977, 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea, Ec, Ej-k, En-o, Eq-r, Et). Stands on the eastern slopes and crest are adjacent to those of <i>Pinus jeffreyi, Artemisia tridentata,</i> and <i>Purshia tridentata</i> alliances in Kings Canyon, Sequoia, and Yosemite national parks (Keeler- Wolf et al. 2003b, S. Haultain, pers. comm. 2002), including isolated stands on the western side in the Kern and Kings River drainages on calcareous substrates. Stands are also known near crests above Slinkard Valley (Boul et al. 2021a)</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fe). Stands occur on the upper slopes of the San Emigdio Range.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands are common in the Inyo, Panamint, and White mountains (Thomas et al. 2004), including noncalcareous sites at Whippoorwill Flat RNA (Cheng 2004). Stands are sporadic in the Argus Range at the highest elevations.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb, Bd-e, Bg-h, Bm, Bp). Stands are common on the northern slopes of the San Bernardino and San Gabriel mountains and on the eastern escarpment of the San Jacinto Mountains. The southernmost stands in the state occupy upper, dry slopes on Villager Peak in the Santa Rosa Mountains in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, Dd, Df-m). We know of stands from Goosenest, Medicine Lake Highlands, Mount McGee, and Whaleback Mountain.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cercocarpus ledifolius </i>is a slow growing, drought-tolerant species that can inhabit nutrient poor sites. It does not sprout under most conditions and is not well adapted to recovery following high-intensity and extensive fire (Marshall 1995a). Growing in small and clumped stands near ridgetops and on nutrient-poor sites that do not support dense vegetation may provide some protection from fire. Stands in the Great Basin do not exhibit successful seedling recruitment (Schultz et al. 1991), and many stands are being lost in wildfires (Young et al. 2007).  <i>C. ledifolius</i> is valued by native ungulates and is often heavily grazed, especially in winter (NatureServe 2019). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
